<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-04-12T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-04-12T12:00:00-05:00" n="651" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d651">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">814.00/394: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the Minister in Guatemala</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">McMillin</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-04-12T13:00:00-04:00"><hi rend="italic">April 12,
                                            1920—1 p.m.</hi></date></dateline></opener>
                            <p>36. Department’s April 11, 2 p.m.</p>
                            <p>You will impress upon Estrada Cabrera and upon the leaders of the
                                Unionists the importance of an immediate armistice and a conference
                                in order that the lives of foreigners in Guatemala City may not be
                                further endangered.</p>
                            <p>You will intimate orally to the Unionists that whatever may be the
                                result of the conference they should proceed in strict accordance
                                with the provisions of the Constitution of Guatemala in order to
                                ensure recognition of any future government which may be formed.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Colby</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>